---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Ring Galaxies - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Ring Galaxies</h1>
        
        <div class="infobox">
            <h3 class="infobox-title">Ring Galaxies</h3>
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Type:</th>
                    <td>Galaxy morphology</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Frequency:</th>
                    <td>~20% of spirals (resonant)<br>
                        ~0.01% of all galaxies (collisional)</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Examples:</th>
                    <td><WikiLink slug="pages/Hoags_Object" text="Hoag's Object" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Cartwheel_Galaxy" text="Cartwheel Galaxy" /></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Related:</th>
                    <td><WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Morphology" text="Galaxy Morphology" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Mergers" text="Galaxy Mergers" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Resonances" text="Resonances" /></td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Ring galaxies</strong> are a class of galaxies characterized by a ring-like appearance of stars and gas surrounding a central region. They represent an uncommon but important morphological feature that provides insights into <WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Evolution" text="galaxy evolution" />, <WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Dynamics" text="dynamics" />, and <WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Interactions" text="interactions" />.</p>

        <h2 id="section-0">Types of Ring Galaxies</h2>
        
        <h3>Resonant Ring Galaxies</h3>
        <p>The most common type, found in ~20% of <WikiLink slug="pages/Spiral_Galaxies" text="spiral galaxies" />:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Form through internal dynamics and resonances</li>
            <li>Associated with <WikiLink slug="pages/Spiral_Density_Waves" text="spiral density waves" /></li>
            <li>Often linked to <WikiLink slug="pages/Lindblad_Resonances" text="Lindblad resonances" /> (inner and outer)</li>
            <li>Can be triggered by <WikiLink slug="pages/Bar_Formation" text="bars" /> or oval distortions</li>
        </ul>

        <h3><WikiLink slug="pages/Collisional_Ring_Galaxies" text="Collisional Ring Galaxies" /></h3>
        <p>Rare systems (~0.01% of all galaxies) formed through galaxy collisions:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Result from head-on collisions between galaxies</li>
            <li>"Bullet" galaxy passes through disk center</li>
            <li>Creates expanding density wave</li>
            <li>Short-lived (few 100 Myr)</li>
            <li>Often show enhanced star formation</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-1">Formation Mechanisms</h2>

        <h3>Resonant Formation</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>Bar or oval distortion develops in disk</li>
            <li>Creates resonances at specific radii</li>
            <li>Gas accumulates at resonance locations</li>
            <li>Enhanced star formation creates visible ring</li>
        </ol>

        <h3>Collisional Formation</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>Smaller galaxy ("bullet") approaches larger disk</li>
            <li>Head-on collision through disk center</li>
            <li>Creates outward-propagating density wave</li>
            <li>Compression triggers star formation in expanding ring</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="section-2">Observational Properties</h2>

        <h3>Morphology</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Ring radii typically 3-10 kpc (local universe)</li>
            <li>Can be complete or partial rings</li>
            <li>Often clumpy, especially at high redshift<sup>[2]</sup></li>
            <li>May show spiral features within ring</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Star Formation</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Enhanced SFR in ring regions</li>
            <li>Blue colors indicating young stellar populations</li>
            <li>Strong emission lines (Hα, [OII])</li>
            <li>Often lie on or above <WikiLink slug="pages/Star_Formation_Main_Sequence" text="star-forming main sequence" /><sup>[2]</sup></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Kinematics</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Resonant rings: normal disk rotation</li>
            <li>Collisional rings: expansion velocities ~50-100 km/s</li>
            <li>Complex velocity fields in merging systems</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-3">High-Redshift Ring Galaxies</h2>

        <p>Recent <WikiLink slug="pages/JWST" text="JWST" /> discoveries have revealed ring galaxies at unprecedented redshifts:</p>

        <div class="evidence-for">
            <h4>Notable High-z Examples</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>z=4.0148 candidate - possibly most distant known<sup>[2]</sup></li>
                <li>Multiple systems at z>2 discovered by JWST</li>
                <li>Generally more clumpy than local rings</li>
                <li>Higher SFRs than local counterparts</li>
                <li>Smaller physical sizes in some cases</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h3>Evolution with Redshift</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Number density evolution debated</li>
            <li>Some models predict constant formation rate</li>
            <li>Others suggest increase with cosmic time</li>
            <li>Selection effects favor star-forming rings at high-z<sup>[2]</sup></li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-4">Ring Galaxies as Contaminants</h2>

        <p>Ring galaxies pose challenges for <WikiLink slug="pages/Gravitational_Lens_Surveys" text="gravitational lens surveys" />:<sup>[2]</sup></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Can mimic <WikiLink slug="pages/Einstein_Rings" text="Einstein rings" /></li>
            <li>Similar morphology to galaxy-galaxy lenses</li>
            <li>Difficult to distinguish without spectroscopy</li>
            <li>Significant contamination in automated searches</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-5">Scientific Importance</h2>

        <h3>As Dynamical Laboratories</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Test theories of density wave propagation</li>
            <li>Study gas dynamics and star formation triggers</li>
            <li>Probe galaxy collision physics</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>As Evolutionary Tracers</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Potential tracers of merger rates<sup>[2]</sup></li>
            <li>Indicators of disk stability</li>
            <li>Probes of gas content evolution</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-6">Challenges and Open Questions</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>What determines ring longevity?</li>
            <li>How common are rings at high redshift?</li>
            <li>Can rings reform after disruption?</li>
            <li>What fraction of mergers produce rings?</li>
            <li>How to efficiently separate from gravitational lenses?</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-7">Future Prospects</h2>

        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Euclid_Mission" text="Euclid" /> will find many ring candidates</li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Rubin_LSST" text="LSST" /> will provide large statistical samples</li>
            <li>JWST enabling detailed high-z studies</li>
            <li>Need for automated classification methods</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-8">See Also</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Collisional_Ring_Galaxies" text="Collisional Ring Galaxies" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Morphology" text="Galaxy Morphology" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Resonances" text="Galactic Resonances" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Gravitational_Lensing" text="Gravitational Lensing" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Galaxy_Mergers" text="Galaxy Mergers" /></li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-9">References</h2>
        <ol class="references">
            <li>Buta, R. & Combes, F. (1996) - "Galactic Rings" Fund. Cosmic Phys. 17, 95</li>
            <li>Vizgan et al. (2026) - "JWST's PEARLS: A clumpy ring galaxy at z=4.0148" arXiv:2603.11575</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="page-tags">
            <strong>Tags:</strong>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Galaxy_Morphology" text="Galaxy Morphology" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Galaxy_Dynamics" text="Galaxy Dynamics" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Rare_Objects" text="Rare Objects" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_High_Redshift" text="High Redshift" />
        </div>
  </main>
</Base>
